---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Jay Lee - Enterprise AI Adoption & Human-Agent Work Systems"
  description="Portfolio and writing by Jay Lee on enterprise AI adoption, workflow audits, eval gates, and human-agent operations."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Enterprise AI adoption / evals / workflow systems</p>
      <h1>Make AI adoption measurable before it scales.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        I build public-safe tools and field notes for turning messy enterprise workflows into AI pilot candidates, eval gates,
        owner roles, and value-realization evidence.
      </p>
      <div class="actions">
        <a class="button primary" href="/projects/">View projects</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/writing/">Read notes</a>
      </div>
      <div class="metrics" aria-label="Portfolio proof points">
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>20/20</strong>
          <span>portable workflow eval cases passing in the public kit</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>6/6</strong>
          <span>synthetic RAG eval cases with offline deterministic mode</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric">
          <strong>0</strong>
          <span>employer or customer data used in public artifacts</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <figure class="evidence-panel">
      <img src="/assets/audit-flow.svg" alt="AI workflow audit process from sample workflow documents to adoption roadmap" />
      <figcaption class="panel-caption">
        The core pattern: diagnose the workflow, define eval evidence, keep human accountability visible.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Current focus</p>
        <h2>Human-agent work systems, not generic AI demos.</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        The work here is built for enterprise conversations where the hard question is not whether AI can answer, but what
        should change, who owns the step, and what evidence proves readiness.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Workflow audit</h3>
        <p>Map owners, baselines, sensitivity, pilot candidates, and adoption roadmaps before proposing tools.</p>
        <div class="tag-row">
          <span class="tag">AI adoption</span>
          <span class="tag">pilot scope</span>
        </div>
        <a href="/projects/">See the project</a>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Eval gates</h3>
        <p>Use synthetic fixtures, failure boundaries, and pass/fail criteria to keep demos from becoming unsupported rollout claims.</p>
        <div class="tag-row">
          <span class="tag">RAG</span>
          <span class="tag">evidence</span>
        </div>
        <a href="/writing/ai-workflow-audit-kit/">Read the first note</a>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Responsible capture</h3>
        <p>Separate team-owned process knowledge from private style, identity, or unapproved person-grounded data.</p>
        <div class="tag-row">
          <span class="tag">human review</span>
          <span class="tag">governance</span>
        </div>
        <a href="https://github.com/jayjoolee/ai-workflow-audit-kit/blob/main/docs/responsible-skill-capture.md">Open doc</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="quote-band">
    <section class="section">
      <p>Do not clone the person. Diagnose the workflow. Prove value before scaling.</p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Open-source tools</p>
        <h2>Small tools from the same workbench.</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        Local-first, privacy-respecting utilities that keep the building muscle honest: shipped code anyone can run,
        not just frameworks on slides.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>photo-trip-timeline</h3>
        <p>Auto-detect trips from Apple Photos into a shareable Markdown timeline — GPS never leaves your Mac.</p>
        <div class="tag-row">
          <span class="tag">local-first</span>
          <span class="tag">privacy</span>
        </div>
        <a href="https://github.com/jayjoolee/photo-trip-timeline">Open GitHub repository</a>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>claude-voice-memo</h3>
        <p>Voice recording → speaker-aware transcript + key briefing, fully local with on-device Whisper.</p>
        <div class="tag-row">
          <span class="tag">on-device STT</span>
          <span class="tag">Claude Code</span>
        </div>
        <a href="https://github.com/jayjoolee/claude-voice-memo">Open GitHub repository</a>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>dopamind</h3>
        <p>ADHD-friendly learning: long content broken into focused chunks with hooks and catch-me-up recaps.</p>
        <div class="tag-row">
          <span class="tag">learning</span>
          <span class="tag">BYOK</span>
        </div>
        <a href="https://github.com/jayjoolee/dopamind">Open GitHub repository</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Writing</p>
        <h2>Build notes from the public workbench.</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        Articles connect code, adoption method, and operating judgment. Each one should point back to a public artifact or
        a decision pattern that can be inspected.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="article-list">
      <a class="article-row" href="/writing/ai-workflow-audit-kit/">
        <span class="article-date">Build note</span>
        <span>
          <h3>From workflow descriptions to AI pilot candidates</h3>
          <p>
            Why the AI Workflow Audit Kit starts with owners, baselines, risk boundaries, and eval evidence instead of a
            model demo.
          </p>
        </span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
